{"serial": "12007", "department_serial": 13, "code": "EL1202", "class": "*", "name": {"en": "Literature, History and Philosophy", "ch": "文學、歷史與哲思"}, "notice": {"en": "", "ch": ""}, "instructor": {"en": ["Laura Perez Leon"], "ch": ["柏伶"]}, "credits": 3, "time_loc": [{"time": {"week": 5, "session": ["2", "3", "4"]}, "loc": {"building": "C2", "room": "114"}}], "isRequired": false, "isFullSem": false, "MaxStu": 50, "department": {"ch": "英美語文學系", "en": "Department of English"}, "system": {"ch": "學士班", "en": "Undergraduate Programme"}, "language": {"ch": "英語", "en": "English"}, "card": {"ch": "部份使用", "en": "Optional"}, "assigned": 49, "selected": 0, "remark": {"ch": "", "en": ""}, "goal": {"ch": "Please refer to English version.", "en": "LIMITED TO ENGLISH FRESHMEN. \nThis course was specifically designed for English \nFreshmen. If you are not a first-year student majoring in \nEnglish, you will not be allowed to enroll. Bear in mind that  \nno additional course cards will be provided to non-English \nfreshmen. \n\nOverview: Literature, History and Philosophy seeks to \nprovide students with conceptual tools for examining \nquestions, methodological puzzles, and views around the\nthree modes of inquiry: (i) Fiction; (ii) History and \n(iii) Philosophy."}, "outline": {"ch": "Please refer to English version.", "en": "ALL COURSE CONTENT WILL BE DELIVERED IN\nENGLISH.\nFor the course content, we will examine the following\nPROBLEMS: (1) Why should we care about the\nhumanities? (2) What is the purpose of literature?\n(3) What does it mean to know, represent, and explain the\n“past”? (4) What is the feasibility of doing philosophy?"}, "textbook": {"ch": "Please refer to English version.", "en": "Main references:\n\n* Eagleton, Terry, “What is Literature?” In Goldblatt, David, Lee B. Brown ＆ Stephanie Patridge (eds.) Aesthetics. A Reader in Philosophy of the Arts, Fourth Edition, Routledge, 2018, pp. 265-269.  \n* Koselleck, Reinhart, 2002, The Practice of Conceptual \nHistory: Timing History, Spacing Concepts, Stanford \nUniversity Press. \n* Kroon, Fred ＆ Alberto Voltolini, 2019, “Fiction,” In \nStanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy. \n* John, Eileen ＆ Dominic McIver Lopes, 2004, The \nPhilosophy of Literature: Contemporary and Classic \nReadings. An Anthology, Wiley-Blackwell.  \n* Little, Daniel, 2010, New Contributions to the Philosophy of History, Springer Science. \n* Nussbaum, Martha C., 2016, Not for Profit: Why \nDemocracy Needs the Humanities, Princeton University \nPress. \n* Walton, Kendall, 2008, Marvelous Images: On Values \nand the Arts, Oxford University Press. \n* Watson, Lani, 2020, “Educating for Good Questioning as a Democratic Skill.” In Fricker, Miranda, Peter J. Graham, David Henderson, and Nikolaj J.L.L. Pedersen (eds.) The \nRoutledge Handbook of Social Epistemology, Routledge, pp. 437-446. \n\nThe course guide is ready to be photocopied at 高冠 (Gao \nChan). Do not photocopy this material if you are not already \nenrolled in my course."}, "selfCompiledRate": {"ch": "0%", "en": "0%"}, "instructMethod": {"ch": "講授\n研討", "en": ["Lecture", "Seminar"]}, "gradMethod": {"ch": "Please refer to English version.", "en": "ATTENDING THE FIRST CLASS IS \nMANDATORY.\n\nWORK FOR THE COURSE: \nWeekly Attendance: 20％ \n[With more than two absences, \nthe student will automatically fail the course. Please, \nbear this in mind.]\nWeekly Classroom Participation: 20％ \nMidterm Collective Presentation: 30％\nFinal Collective Assignment: 30％"}, "officeHour": {"ch": "Please refer to English version.", "en": "Only by appointment on Friday from 2 to 3 pm."}, "teachWeeks": {"ch": "16+2", "en": "16+2"}, "flexDiscription": {"ch": "Please refer to English version.", "en": "Independent learning."}, "domain": {"ch": "文化研究\n\n\n、\n\n\n文學與文化研究", "en": "文化研究\n\n\n、\n\n\n文學與文化研究"}, "map": {"ch": [{"competencies": "英文閱讀解析與寫作論述", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["口頭報告/口試", "出席/課堂表現"]}, {"competencies": "英語溝通與文化跨越", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["口